 and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: (i) relationship name from Old Scandinavian  <i>Ívarr</i>,  <i>Iwar</i>,  <i>Ivar</i> ‘yew-army’. (ii) relationship name, possibly from the Welsh male given name  <i>Ifor</i>; if so, it is not clear that it survives today."],"variants":[{"name":"Ivers","meanings":["Irish: from <b>Ó hÍomhair</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Íomhar</i>’, a Gaelic form of the Old Norse personal name <i>Ívarr</i> (see   Iverson   2), with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. It is occasionally Anglicized as   Howard  . Also a shortened form of <b>Mac Íomhair</b> ‘son of <i>Íomhar</i>’, with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. See   McIver  .","North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Ivar</i> (see   Iversen  ).","English: variant of <b>Iver</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, a habitational name from Iver (Buckinghamshire) named from Old English <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place called with the same word."]},{"name":"Iver","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Iver (Bucks) named from Old English * <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place named with the same word.","2  Scottish: (i) relationship name, reduced form of Irish and Scottish Gaelic  <b>Mac Íomhair</b>,  see  McIvor  . (ii) relationship name from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Ivar</i>;  see  Ivor  ."]},{"name":"Iverson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Iver, Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Selmer, Thor, Evald, Gunner, Helmer, Ingman, Jarl, Joneen.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Iversen   and of Swedish <b>Ivarsson</b> (see   Ivarson  ), all cognates of 2 below.","English (Kent and London): patronymic from Old Norse <i>Ívarr</i>, <i>Iwar</i>, <i>Ivar</i>, a compound of either <i>ív</i> ‘yew tree, bow’ or <i>Ing</i> (the name of a god) + <i>ar</i> ‘warrior’ or ‘spear’. Alternatively, the name might be a patronymic from the Welsh male personal name <i>Ifor</i>, itself from British Celtic <i>Iūdomāros</i> ‘lord’ + ‘great’, but if so, it is not clear that it survives today."]}]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘ardour’; borne in the Middle Ages by various rulers in south-west Wales, including  Rhys ap Tewdur  (  d. 1093 ) and  Rhys ap Gruffudd  (  1132–97 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Reece","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Rhys . The name is now in widespread and frequent use outside Wales, in many cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the given name."]},{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Welsh Rhys, in some cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the Welsh given name."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Rhys Ap Ifor was born in 1277, in Penderyn, Breconshire, Wales. She had at least 3 sons with Rhys ap Ifor. She died after 1299."},"et":{"1277–after 1299":"1277–pärast 1299","1275–1299":"1275–1299","1300–1367":"1300–1367","–1350":"–1350","1277–1299":"1277–1299","1367":"1367","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1299":"1299","1275":"1275","1350":"1350","about 1300":"umbes 1300","after 1299":"pärast 1299","Penderyn, Breconshire, Wales":"Penderyn, Breconshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"1277–after 1299":"1277–1299 jälkeen","1275–1299":"1275–1299","1300–1367":"1300–1367","–1350":"–1350","1277–1299":"1277–1299","1367":"1367","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1299":"1299","1275":"1275","1350":"1350","about 1300":"noin 1300","after 1299":"1299 jälkeen","Penderyn, Breconshire, Wales":"Penderyn, Breconshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"1277–after 1299":"1277–après 1299","1275–1299":"1275–1299","1300–1367":"1300–1367","–1350":"–1350","1277–1299":"1277–1299","1367":"1367","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1299":"1299","1275":"1275","1350":"1350","about 1300":"environ 1300","a